SIMPLE: treason
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treason
<hw>Trea"son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tresun</ets>, <ets>treisun</ets>, <ets>traisoun</ets>, OF.
<ets>tra⟦ium⟧son</ets>, F. <ets>trahison</ets>, L. <ets>traditio</ets> a
giving up, a delivering up, fr. <ets>tradere</ets> to give up, betray.
See <er>Traitor</er>, and cf. <er>Tradition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The offense of attempting to overthrow the government of the state
to which the offender owes allegiance, or of betraying the state into
the hands of a foreign power; disloyalty; treachery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>treason</qex> of the murthering in the bed.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In monarchies, the killing of the sovereign, or an
attempt to take his life, is treason. In England, to imagine or compass
the death of the king, or of the queen consort, or of the heir apparent
to the crown, is <xex>high treason</xex>, as are many other offenses
created by statute. In the United States, treason is confined to the
actual levying of war against the United States, or to an adhering to
their enemies, giving them aid and comfort.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Loosely, the betrayal of any trust or confidence;
treachery; perfidy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he be false, she shall his <qex>treason</qex> see.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Petit treason</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Petit</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treasonable</ent>⟦br⟧
